US Airlines Sentiment Analysis Using Twitter Data¶

By:

Ujwala Dharanikota

Introduction:¶

In modern digital age companies are not following traditional methods of contacting customers by phone, addressing customer grievances when they physically come to your outlet is a thing of the past. One of the most heavily used medium to gauge customer sentiment about a particular brand is social media. Companies are finding ways to use this data available on social media sites to acquiring customers, retaining customers and grow more business.

The idea of the project is to take the Twitter data and analyze what the customers are saying about the US Airline companies and their services on social media and how can they improve their services and grow business based on the twitter feeds.

We are doing analysis on Six Airline companies - United, US Airways, American, Southwest, Delta and Virgin America.

Questions:

  1. In which areas of Airline service do customers face maximum issues?
  2. Which model best fits our data to predict the sentiment of the tweets?
  3. From which part of US more negative tweets are coming and the corresponding nearest airports to them?
  4. How airline companies can make use of this analysis to improve their business?

Dataset:¶

The Dataset contains 14640 tweets from 7700 users. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015. The dataset set includes the Attributes - tweet_id, airline_sentiment, airline_sentiment_confidence, negativereason, negativereason_confidence, airline, airline_sentiment_gold, name, negativereason_gold, retweet_count,text, tweet_coord, tweet_created, tweet_location, user_timezone.

Defining functions to count the frequency of each negative reason for each and every Airline

In [18]:
def NR_Count(Airline):
    if Airline=='All':
        df=T_Data_Reason
    else:
        df=T_Data_Reason[T_Data['airline']==Airline]
    count=dict(df['negativereason'].value_counts())
    Unique_reason=list(T_Data_Reason['negativereason'].unique())
    Unique_reason=[x for x in Unique_reason if str(x) != 'nan']
    Reason_frame=pd.DataFrame({'Reasons':Unique_reason})
    Reason_frame['count']=Reason_frame['Reasons'].apply(lambda x: count[x])
    return Reason_frame
In [19]:
def plot_reason(Airline):
    df=NR_Count(Airline)
    count=df['count']
    Index = range(1,(len(df)+1))
    plt.bar(Index,count)
    plt.xticks(Index,df['Reasons'],rotation=90)
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.xlabel('Reason')
    plt.title('Count of Reasons for '+Airline)

In [24]:
def tweet_to_words(raw_tweet):
    letters_only = re.sub("[^a-zA-Z]", " ",raw_tweet)
    words = letters_only.lower().split()                             
    stops = set(stopwords.words("english"))                  
    meaningful_words = [w for w in words if not w in stops] 
    return( " ".join( meaningful_words ))

Cleaning the tweet by making a list of stopwords and removing them from the tweet

In [25]:
def clean_tweet_length(raw_tweet):
    letters_only = re.sub("[^a-zA-Z]", " ",raw_tweet) 
    words = letters_only.lower().split()                             
    stops = set(stopwords.words("english"))                  
    meaningful_words = [w for w in words if not w in stops] 
    return(len(meaningful_words))

In [53]:
dense_features=train_features.toarray()
dense_test= test_features.toarray()
Accuracy=[]
Model=[]
for classifier in Classifiers:
    try:
        fit = classifier.fit(train_features,train['sentiment'])
        pred = fit.predict(test_features)
    except Exception:
        fit = classifier.fit(dense_features,train['sentiment'])
        pred = fit.predict(dense_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(pred,test['sentiment'])
    Accuracy.append(accuracy)
    Model.append(classifier.__class__.__name__)
    print('Accuracy of '+classifier.__class__.__name__+' is '+str(accuracy))

Merging information from 2 datasets and assigning each tweet with location data to an airport based on proximity. Assuming that a tweet about an airline came from the airport closest to the location of tweet. Computed distance between tweet location and the closest airport from the top 30 airports, and assign airport for each tweet with location data.

In [31]:
T_Data['airport_name'] = '';
T_Data['airport_city'] = '';
T_Data['airport_state'] = '';
T_Data['airport_lat'] = 0.0;
T_Data['airport_lon'] = 0.0;



for i in range(0,len(T_Data['latitude'])):
    d_all = 0;
    if (T_Data['latitude'][i]!=0):
        d_all = (df_airport['latitude']-T_Data['latitude'][i])**2+(df_airport['longitude']-T_Data['longitude'][i])**2
        ind_min = np.argmin(d_all)
        #print i,df_airport['latitude'][ind_min];
        T_Data['airport_name'][i]=df_airport['name'][ind_min]
        T_Data['airport_city'][i]=df_airport['city'][ind_min]
        T_Data['airport_state'][i]=df_airport['State'][ind_min]
        T_Data['airport_lat'][i] = df_airport['latitude'][ind_min];
        T_Data['airport_lon'][i] = df_airport['longitude'][ind_min];

There are many missing values for latitude and longitude columns which limits our analysis about which airline company in which airport is having what kind of service issue. Out of the 14640 tweets, only 841 had data on location.

Conclusion:¶

-> I found that more than 60% of the tweets had negative sentiment.

-> I further analysed the data by airlines and found that United, US Airways, and American have a bigger fraction of negative sentiments than the other three.

-> The reasons for negative sentiments have different weights for different airlines. In general, customer service issues is the most common reason for all airlines. Delta and United customes faces major isuues with flight delays.

Using this analysis Airline companies can concentrate on their services in specific airports and provide best customer experience and improve their business.

This analysis gave us a sense of what customers care about and unsatisfied with the airlines, and how airlines can improve their service to provide better customers satisfaction.

Future Scope¶

-> Which gender of customers are having more issues

-> Which age group people are having issues
